english:
  title: Record of the Great Harmony Gate Tower in Pyongyang Fortress
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Pyongyang is a great garrison city of our realm—a passage for envoys, a gathering place for armies. Yet its walls have crumbled, and through the long years no repairs have been made. Its eastern gate is called the Great Harmony Gate, its southern gate the Clasping Sphere Gate; both were consumed by fire during the calamities of the Year of the Metal Ox. With defenses thus weakened, all cause for concern was warranted.

    In the autumn of the Jiasheng year under the Hongwu reign, when the Prince first ascended the throne, he commanded Minister Zhao Wen of the State Council to become Governor of Pyongyang. The following year, when governance flourished and legal disputes were fairly settled, the common people found peace in their livelihoods. That autumn, by royal command, the old city walls were at last restored. The next spring, two new gates were constructed, and by autumn the work was complete.

    Then a letter came to me, urgently requesting this record. It said: "Pyongyang is a place of heavy burdens—both military and civil—where customs run fierce and dull, long accounted difficult to govern. Though I lack the talent, I have been fortunate to serve in the early days of our founding, bearing unworthy the weight of this great trust. Coming to this place, I have devoted myself, day and night, to strengthening our defenses. The walls we built in the farming season, the gates we completed with labor drawn from all. The people came forth to aid the work, and three seasons sufficed for completion. Now that the watchtower stands magnificent and the city's perimeter is whole, at last we may call it a true bulwark of the realm. Yet this is not my doing—it is the virtue of the King. I beg you write this account upon the gate's beam, so that those who come after may know how what was lost was raised again."

    To this I reply:

    Pyongyang is none other than the capital of Ki Tzu of ancient Gojoseon, where the Nine Categories revealed the learning of heaven and humanity, and the Eight Ordinances demonstrated virtue's beauty. Here was sown the deep soil of our Eastern realm's rites and righteous instruction spanning millennia. Alas, how magnificent! Yet from the days of Wei Man through Goguryeo, might alone was venerated, and the customs greatly transformed. In Goryeo's time, with Liao, Jin, and Yuan as neighbors across the border, barbarous ways seeped into the land, deepening its fierceness and pride. It is like the lands of Qi and Feng: the Zhou used them to cultivate benevolence and thickness of heart, while Qin used them to forge courage and savage vigor. The nature of this people is grave and honest; lead them toward the good, and they follow readily; drive them with severity, and they prove capable of building a strong and prosperous realm.

    Consider now: the Bright Dynasty's Emperor holds all under heaven and proclaims supreme governance. Our Prince serves the greater power with sincerity and rules his people with magnanimity. Receiving the Emperor's mandate, he restored Joseon's name. This official comes bearing compassion and gentle wisdom, first entrusted with this heavy charge, arriving to govern this city. Surely he shall unfold virtue's teaching, guide his people toward goodness, and transform the old customs of fierceness and pride into a flourishing of rites and righteousness. His gentle ways shall restore simplicity to these lands, bringing aid to the prosperous and renewed rule of this great age. Such transformation begins here.

    But see—is this merely a matter of stronger walls and grander gates surpassing what was before? I envision standing upon that tower, gazing down at the long river, watching the open plains stretch away. Morning radiance and evening moonlight, ten thousand scenes and moods, all gather beneath the eaves. Without laboring to travel afar, without climbing to distant heights, one beholds the full beauty of the realm at a glance.

    Should fortune grant me to ascend that tower someday, I shall first speak to the people of the Sovereign's teaching, so they understand how deep Ki Tzu's grace has run through these Eastern lands—a current that ten thousand ages cannot dry. The Emperor's gift of our nation's name and the Prince's restoration of our ancient seat mirror exactly the Wu King's enfeoffment of Ki Tzu and Ki Tzu's governance of Joseon. And let the people know that the inborn nature needs no distinction between civilized and barbarian, ancient and modern. Should they but strive to follow the Sovereign's Way, then heaven and earth shall accord, and their descendants shall know blessing. Thus shall they grasp the meaning of Great Harmony.

    Then, with a few companions, I shall drink in the wind and contemplate the beauty of mountains and rivers, let my spirit roam and delight. For you, I shall compose a poem of praise and celebration.

    [Written] in the ninth month of the twenty-seventh year of Hongwu, year of the Wood Dog.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ki Tzu (箕子): A legendary sage-king of ancient Gojoseon who is credited with bringing civilization and moral teaching to the Korean peninsula. The ''Nine Categories'' and ''Eight Ordinances'' refer to teachings attributed to him.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Great Harmony (大同, Dae Tong): References the Confucian ideal of a perfectly ordered society, embodying universal benevolence and righteous governance.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Year of the Metal Ox (辛丑): This refers to 1361, when the Goryeo dynasty faced internal strife and barbarian incursions.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wei Man and the historical rulers mentioned: The text traces Pyongyang''s history through various periods, noting how military values gradually replaced the moral teachings of Ki Tzu.'
